{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17515694","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17515694"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:33:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:33:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12486"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12486","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12486"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.55,0.25,0.17,0.03,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4993"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"37655"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4993","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4993"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12486"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"22223"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"11676"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8272"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8966"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9306"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"37655","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/37655"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old woman presents with a 24 hour history of intermittent dizziness, nausea and vomiting. She describes the dizziness as \u0022the room spinning around me\u0022. The dizziness is not always present and seem to occur most when she changes positions, such as when she stands up or turns her head quickly. She denies any recent head trauma, ear infections, or significant changes in her daily activities. Her history includes depression, for which she is being treated with escitalopram. She has no other past medical history. A neurological exam reveals no focal deficits and no ataxia but her dizziness and nausea are exacerbated by the Dix Hallpike manoeuvre.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate antiemetic for her nausea and vomiting?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Promethazine","Ondansetron","Metoclopramide","Dexamethasone","Haloperidol"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has presented with nausea, vomiting and a feeling of intermittent dizziness that is exacerbated by the Dix Hallpike Manoeuvre, thus indicating a vestibular cause of her condition most likely benign paroxysmal positional vertigo. The most appropriate antiemetic for managing the patient\u0027s nausea and vomiting is \u003Cstrong\u003Epromethazine\u003C/strong\u003E. Promethazine is an antihistamine H1 blocker, effective for motion sickness and vertigo and can be used for elevated intracranial pressure. Promethazine acts by blocking H1 receptors, which reduces vestibular stimulation and inhibits the central emetic pathways. By targeting these pathways, promethazine effectively alleviates symptoms of nausea and vomiting in patients experiencing vestibular disturbances.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Eondansetron\u003C/strong\u003E is a 5HT3 receptor antagonist that is most effective for nausea and vomiting associated with chemotherapy and radiotherapy, it is not the most appropriate choice for the patient\u0027s condition in this case. Ondansetron primarily targets the 5HT3 receptors in the gastrointestinal tract and central nervous system, making it particularly effective in those specific settings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetoclopramide\u003C/strong\u003E is a pro-kinetic agent effective for gastric stasis and failure of peristalsis. It is not the most suitable agent for this patient\u0027s symptoms because they are due to a vestibular cause. not a gastric motility issue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDexamethasone \u003C/strong\u003Eis a steroid used for elevated intracranial pressure and for the combination treatment of nausea in chemotherapy patients. Although it may have some antiemetic properties, it is not the most appropriate choice for the patient\u0027s condition described in the clinical scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaloperidol\u003C/strong\u003E targets the chemoreceptor trigger zone and is a D2 antagonist. It is effective for chemical causes of nausea and vomiting and also has dual action for patients also experiencing agitation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Promethazine is the most effective antiemetic for vestibular causes of nausea and vomiting"],"references":["Athavale A, Athavale T, Roberts DM. Antiemetic drugs: what to prescribe and when. Aust Prescr. 2020 Apr;43(2):49-56. doi: 10.18773/austprescr.2020.011. Epub 2020 Apr 1. PMID: 32346211; PMCID: PMC7186277.","Southard BT, Al Khalili Y. Promethazine. 2022 Jul 21. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan\u2013. PMID: 31335081."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"22223"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12486"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"22223","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/22223"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-07-03T10:46:06+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-29T09:45:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4993"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"37655"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position"